<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-21T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="537" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">803.24/1048: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-21T19:00:00+03:00">April 21,
                                    1941—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received April 21—6:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>819. My 786, April 16, 7 p.m.<note n="74" xml:id="d537fn1">
                                <ref target="frus1941v04#pg_955">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>,
                                    p. 955</ref>.</note> The [Chinese Ambassador made the
                            statement?] that he has now received “a satisfactory reply” to his
                            inquiry of the Soviet Government concerning continued assistance to
                            Chiang Kai-shek. As there were Axis diplomats present at our meeting I
                            did not press him for details.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>